nships|2017 Budapest]]|Ball}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships|2019 Baku]]|Ball}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2019 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships|2019 Baku]]|Ribbon}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|Grand Prix Final]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2016 Eilat]] |All-around}}\n{{MedalGold| [[List of medalists at the Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Final|2016 Eilat]] |Hoop}}\n{{MedalGold| [[List of medalists at the Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Final|2016 Eilat]] |Ball}}\n{{MedalGold| [[List of medalists at the Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Final|2016 Eilat]] |Clubs}}\n{{MedalGold| [[List of medalists at the Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Final|2016 Eilat]] |Ribbon}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2014 Debrecen]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2015 Lisbon]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Espoo]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Lisbon]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2017 Pesaro]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2017 Minsk]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2018 Sofia]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2018 Tashkent]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2018 Kazan]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2019 Sofia]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2019 Tashkent]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2019 Guadalajara]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalGold|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2019 Portimao]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2015 Tashkent]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Tashkent]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Minsk]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Guadalajara]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2017 Baku]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2018 Guadalajara]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2018 Minsk]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2014 Tashkent]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2015 Pesaro]]|All-around}}\n\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2015 Kazan]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Kazan]]|All-around}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2016 Baku]]|All-around}}\n|Olympic Games=}}\n\n'''Aleksandra Sergeyevna Soldatova''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430}}; born 1 June 1998 in [[Sterlitamak]], [[Bashkortostan]], [[Russia]]) is a Russian individual [[Rhythmic gymnastics|rhythmic gymnast]]. She is the [[2018 Rhythmic Gymnastics World Championships|2018 World]] All-around bronze medalist, 2018 World ribbon champion, the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2016 Grand Prix Final]] All-around champion and the [[Russian Rhythmic Gymnastics National Championships|2016 Russian National]] All-around champion. On the junior level, she is the [[2012 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships|2012 European Junior]] ribbon champion and two-time [[Russian Rhythmic Gymnastics National Championships|Russian Junior]] National All-around medalist.\n\nShe is coached by [[Anna Shumilova|Anna Shumilova-Dyachenko]].\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Junior  ===\nSoldatova began training in rhythmic gymnastics at age seven. She burst onto the junior international scene at the 2011 Junior [[Irina Deleanu]] Cup where she won gold medal in the all-around and event finals in hoop and ribbon, silver medal in ball. She then competed at the World Club Cup, the 2011 Aeon Cup in Tokyo, Japan, where she won the junior all-around gold together with Team Gazprom (seniors [[Evgenia Kanaeva]] and [[Daria Kondakova]]).<ref>{{cite web|title= GAZPROM and Kanaeva on Top at the 2011 AEON Cup |url=http://www.gymmedia.com/rhythmic-gymnastics/GAZPROM-and-Kanaeva-Top-2011-AEON-Cup |publisher=gymmedia |date=30 October 2011}}</ref> At the Russian National Junior Championships, she won the bronze in 2012<ref>{{cite web|title= 2012 Russian Junior Championships |url=http://r-gymnastics.com/v-kazani-zavershilos-pervenstvo-rossii-po-khudozhestvennoi-gimnastike |publisher=r-gymnastics |date=12 February 2012}}</ref> and silver in 2013 in the all-around.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Russian Junior Championships|url=http://f3.s.qip.ru/uX0nxSRp.jpg|publisher=rg4u.clan|date=10 February 2013|access-date=10 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052428/http://f3.s.qip.ru/uX0nxSRp.jpg|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Soldatova started her season at the 2012 Moscow Grand Prix. She won the all-around gold at the Schmiden International Tournament and all event finals before winning Team gold with [[Dina Averina]] and [[Arina Averina]] at the 2012 MTM Ljubljana. After winning gold in ribbon at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2012 Pesaro Junior World Cup]], she then won the all-around title at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup|2012 Sofia Junior World Cup]] and the event finals. At the [[2012 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships|2012 European Junior Championships]], Soldatova won the gold medal in ribbon as well as helping the Russian junior team (with [[Yana Kudryavtseva]], Julia Sinitsina and [[Diana Borisova]]) win the junior team gold medal.<ref>{{cite web|title= Europeans 2012: Russia with eight of nine Titles! |url=http://www.gymmedia.com/rhythmic-gymnastics/28th-Europeans-Rhythmiic-Gymnastics-2012-Russia-eight-nine-Titles |publisher=gymmedia |date=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nCompeting at the 2013 Russian Spartakiada's 6th Summer Student Games, Soldatova won the all-around gold ahead of the Averina twins, as well as gold in ribbon and silver in clubs and hoop. In October, she was the all-around gold medalist in the junior division in the Italian Serie A.\n\n=== Senior ===\n\n====2014 Season====\nIn the 2014 Season, due to Russia's repository of rhythmic gymnasts, Soldatova was part of the reserve team, and nevertheless made her senior debut competing in the senior international tournament division at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2014 Moscow Grand Prix]] where she won the bronze medal in the All-around behind the Averina Twins (Dina and Arina). Soldatova was assigned to her first World Cup event after replacing Yulia Sinitsina in the entry list for the [[2014 Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2014 Debrecen World Cup]] where Soldatova finished 1st place in the all-around with a total score of 70.750 points, beating [[2013 World Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships|2013 World Silver]] medalist [[Ganna Rizatdinova]] for the gold. In event finals, she won gold in clubs (18.067) and ribbon (17.633), silver in ball (17.583) and bronze in hoop (17.283) points.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexandra Soldatova makes impressive World Cup debut in Debrecen |url=http://www.fedintgym.com/site/node/82 |publisher=Federation International de Gymnastique |date=17 March 2014 |access-date=17 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318001648/http://www.fedintgym.com/site/node/82 |archive-date=18 March 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 4\u20136 April, Soldatova competed at the 2014 Baltic Hoop where she won the all-around gold medal, teammate [[Arina Averina]] took the silver medal and bronze to Belarusian [[Katsiaryna Halkina]]. She won 3 gold medals in event finals: (in hoop, clubs, ribbon) and finished 4th in ball. In 23\u201327 April, Soldatova made her senior national appearance at the [[Russian Rhythmic Gymnastics National Championships|2014 Russian Championships]] where she won the all-around bronze medal behind [[Yana Kudryavtseva]] (gold) and [[Margarita Mamun]] (silver). In 9\u201311 May, Soldatova competed in her second World Cup at the [[2014 Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2014 Corbeil-Essonnes World Cup]] where she finished 4th in all-around behind [[Ganna Rizatdinova]], she qualified to 1 event final winning the silver medal in ball. Soldatova then competed at the [[2014 Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2014 Tashkent World Cup]] winning bronze in the all-around behind teammates [[Margarita Mamun]] and [[Yana Kudryavtseva]] who took the gold and silver medal respectively, she did not advance to the event finals due to the 2 gymnast per country rule, with Mamun and Kudryavtseva placing ahead of her in qualifications. In 4\u20136 July, Soldatova competed at the Izmir Tournament Cup and won the all-around gold ahead of teammate [[Maria Titova]], she qualified to all 4 event finals and won gold in ribbon, 3 silver medals (hoop, ball and clubs). In 16\u201317 August, Soldatova was invited for an international competition meet in [[Vit\u00f3ria, Esp\u00edrito Santo|Vitoria]], [[Brazil]] where she made a sweep of the gold medals with high scores in the all-around (71.500 points) and all event finals  (Hoop:18.150, Ball: 17.650, Clubs: 18.200, Ribbon: 18.000).<ref>{{cite web|title= Alexandra Soldatova sweeps Rhythmic International in Brazil |url=https://www.fig-gymnastics.com/site/figNews/view?id=720 |publisher=Federation International de Gymnastique |date=18 August 2014}}</ref> In 22\u201328 September, Soldatova (along with teammates [[Yana Kudryavtseva]] and [[Margarita Mamun]]) represented [[Russia]] at the [[2014 World Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships|2014 World Championships]], she competed in only 2 apparatus, contributing scores of 17.675 (ball) and 18.050 (hoop) helping Russia win the Team gold medal with a total of 147.914 points. Soldatova did not advance to any event finals because of the 2 gymnast per country rule with [[Yana Kudryavtseva|Kudryavtseva]] and Mamun placed ahead of her in qualifications.\n\n====2015 Season====\n[[File:Soldatova.jpg|thumb|Soldatova in 2015]]\nSoldatova started her season competing at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2015 Moscow Grand Prix]] where she finished 4th in the all-around. She qualified to 2 event finals, taking the gold medal in ball ahead of [[Melitina Staniouta]] and finished 7th in clubs. In 27\u201329 March, Soldatova competed at the [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 Lisboa World Cup]] where she won the all-around gold with a total score of 73.600 points beating compatriots [[Margarita Mamun]] (silver) and [[Yana Kudryavtseva]] (bronze). She qualified to 3 event finals: won gold in clubs, silver in ball and placed 6th in hoop.<ref>{{cite web|title= Aleksandra Soldatova, Italy win Rhythmic season opener in Lisbon |url=http://www.fig-gymnastics.com/site/figNews/view?id=1090 |publisher=Federation International de Gymnastique |date=30 March 2015}}</ref> Her next event, at the [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 Lisboa World Cup]], Soldatova finished 6th in all-around after mistakes and drop from her hoop routine, she qualified to 2 apparatus finals winning gold in ribbon (tied with [[Yana Kudryavtseva]]) and silver in clubs. In 10\u201312 April, Soldatova won the all-around bronze at the [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 Pesaro World Cup]], she qualified to 2 event finals taking gold in ball and bronze in ribbon. Soldatova was selected as member of the Russian team to compete at the [[2015 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships|2015 European Championships]] where they won Team gold (together with teammates [[Yana Kudryavtseva]] and [[Margarita Mamun]]). Soldatova qualified to 2 apparatus however only placed 7th in hoop and 8th in clubs finals. In 15\u201326 May, Soldatova competed at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2015 Holon Grand Prix]], she won silver in ball and ribbon finals. At the [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 Tashkent World Cup]], Soldatova won the all-around silver behind [[Margarita Mamun]], she qualified to all 4 apparatus finals, taking silver (in hoop, ball, ribbon) and placed 6th in clubs. Soldatova's next competition was at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2015 Grand Prix Berlin]] where she won bronze in all-around behind [[Melitina Staniouta]], she qualified to 3 event finals and won silver in (hoop, clubs, ribbon). In August, Soldatova competed at the  [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 Budapest World Cup]] finishing 4th in all-around behind Belarusian [[Melitina Staniouta]], Soldatova only qualified to 1 event final placing 7th in ribbon. In her next competition, Soldatova finished 6th in the all-around at the [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 Sofia World Cup]] and qualified to 1 event final taking silver in clubs behind teammate [[Yana Kudryavtseva|Kudryavtseva]]. At the [[2015 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2015 World Cup series]] in [[Kazan]], Soldatova won the all-around bronze medal with a total of 74.300 points. Soldatova qualified to clubs final, but was given the remaining apparatus finals being the 3rd Russian qualifier in scores, after [[Yana Kudryavtseva|Kudryavtseva]]'s withdrawal from an ankle inflammation sustained in her clubs routine. Soldatova competed in the events suffering from a [[flu]], nevertheless, she only made a few mistakes and won silver medals in Hoop (18.500), Ball (18.450), Clubs (18.300) and Ribbon (18.400) right behind teammate [[Margarita Mamun]] who won all the apparatus finals.<ref>{{cite web|title= In Kudryavtseva's absence, Margarita Mamun, Russians sweep in Kazan |url=http://www.fig-gymnastics.com/site/figNews/view?id=1261 |publisher=Federation International de Gymnastique |date=24 August 2014}}</ref> In 9\u201313 September, At the [[2015 World Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships|2015 World Championships]] in [[Stuttgart]], Soldatova (together with teammates [[Yana Kudryavtseva]] and [[Margarita Mamun]]) represented Russia where they won the Team gold. She competed in 3 apparatus in qualifications and qualified to 2 finals, winning the silver medal in hoop and clubs, she was ranked 3rd for the all-around; however she did not advance into the all-around finals because of the two-per country rule and with Kudryavsteva and Mamun ahead of her in qualification scores.<ref>{{cite web|title= Yana Kudryavtseva (RUS), Russia golden again at Stuttgart Rhythmic Worlds |url=http://www.fig-gymnastics.com/site/figNews/view?id=1296 |publisher=International Federation of Gymnastics |date=10 September 2015}}</ref> In 2\u20134 October, Soldatova together with teammates [[Margarita Mamun]] and junior [[Alina Ermolova]] represented Team Gazprom at the 2015 Aeon Cup in [[Tokyo]] [[Japan]], Soldatova won bronze in the individual all-around finals behind [[Ganna Rizatdinova]] and with Team Russia winning the gold medal in the overall standings. Soldatova qualified for the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2015 Grand Prix Final]] in [[Brno]], but withdrew before the start of the competition because of fever.\n\n====2016 Season====\nIn 2016, Soldatova started her season at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2016 Moscow Grand Prix]] where she won the all-around gold medal with a total of 74.066 points, she qualified to 3 apparatus finals taking gold in hoop, ball and a silver in ribbon.<ref>{{cite web|title= Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix starts into Olympic Season |url=http://www.gymmedia.com/Rhythmic-Gymnastics/Also-Rhythmic-Gymnastics-Grand-Prix-starts-Olympic-Season |publisher=Gymmedia |date=21 February 2016}}.</ref> In 26-28 February, Soldatova competed in the first World Cup of the season at the [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Espoo World Cup]] where she won the all-around gold. In apparatus finals; she won gold in clubs, silver in hoop, bronze in ribbon, placed 4th in ball.<ref>{{cite web|title= Rhythmic World Cup Circuit 2016 started in Finland |url=http://www.gymmedia.com/Rhythmic-Gymnastics/Rhythmic-World-Cup-Circuit-2016-started-Finland |publisher=Gymmedia |date=29 February 2016}}</ref> On 17\u201320 March, Soldatova then competed at the [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Lisboa World Cup]] where she won the all-around gold with a total of 75.650 points (a new Personal Best). In event finals, she won gold in hoop, ball, silver in ribbon (tied with teammate [[Arina Averina]]) and bronze in clubs. At the 30th [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|Thiais Grand Prix]] event in [[Paris]], Soldatova won the all-around silver behind teammate [[Margarita Mamun]], she qualified 3 apparatus finals: taking gold in ball, ribbon and silver in hoop.<ref>{{cite web|title= Grand Prix: 30th International Thiais 2016 |url=http://www.gymmedia.com/Rhythmic-Gymnastics/Grand-Prix-30th-International-Thiais-2016 |publisher=Gymmedia |date=27 March 2016}}</ref> Soldatova won the all-around gold at the [[Russian Rhythmic Gymnastics National Championships|2016 Russian Championships]] held in [[Sochi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gimnastika.pro/press/news/the_results_of_the_russian_championship_2016_in_th.html |title= 2016 Russian Championships|accessdate=2016-04-17}}</ref> On 13\u201315 May, Soldatova competed at the [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Tashkent World Cup]] where she won the all-around silver medal behind [[Yana Kudryavtseva]], she qualified to 3 apparatus finals taking silver in hoop, clubs and ribbon.<ref name=Tashkent2016/> She won another silver medal in the all-around at the [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Minsk World Cup]] with a total of 74.200 points, in the event finals: she won 3 silver medals (ball, ribbon, clubs) and placed 7th in hoop.\n<ref name=WCMinsk16/> On 3\u20135 June, Soldatova then won silver in the all-around at the [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Guadalajara World Cup]] with a new PB score of 75.700 points, in apparatus finals: she won gold in ball, silver in hoop, clubs and bronze in ribbon. On 8\u201310 July, Soldatova won bronze in the all-around at the [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Kazan World Cup]] with a total of 75.500 points, she qualified to 1 apparatus final taking silver in clubs.<ref name=WCKazan16/> On 22\u201324 July, culminating the World Cup of the season in [[2016 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2016 Baku World Cup]], Soldatova won another all-around bronze medal with a total of 75.850 points - updating her Personal Best, she qualified to 1 apparatus final; winning a silver in ball behind [[Margarita Mamun]]. Soldatova traveled as a reserve/alternate individual athlete in Russia's rhythmic gymnastics at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] held in [[Rio de Janeiro]]. On 9\u201311 September, Soldatova together with teammates [[Margarita Mamun]] and junior [[Maria Sergeeva (rhythmic gymnast)|Maria Sergeeva]] represented team [[Gazprom]] at the annual 2016 Aeon Cup in [[Tokyo]], where they won the team gold and with Soldatova taking bronze in individual all-around behind [[Ganna Rizatdinova]]. On 22\u201324 September, Soldatova culminated her season at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2016 Grand Prix Final]] in [[Eilat]], Israel where she won the all-around gold earning a new personal best total of 77.033 points, she also swept gold in all the apparatus finals in Hoop (19.300), Ball (19.367), Clubs (19.200) and Ribbon (19.117).\n\n====2017 Season====\n[[File:Aleksandra Soldatova.jpg|left|thumb|300px|Soldatova at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2017 Grand Prix Moscow]]]]In 2017, Soldatova started her Post-Olympics season in competition at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2017 Grand Prix Moscow]] where she won the all-around silver medal behind teammate [[Dina Averina]], she qualified 2 apparatus finals winning the gold in ball and silver in hoop. On 10\u201312 March, Soldatova competed as the defending champion at the [[Russian Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships|2017 Russian Championships]] where she won the all-around silver medal behind [[Dina Averina|Dina]].<ref name=RusNat17/> On 31 March \u2013 2 April, Soldatova competed at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2017 Grand Prix Marbella]] where she won the all-around gold and swept the gold in all the event finals in hoop (19.350), ball (19.250), clubs (19.500), and ribbon (19.200). On 7\u20139 April, Soldatova competed in the first World Cup of the season at the [[2017 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2017 Pesaro World Cup]] where she won gold in the all-around ahead of teammate [[Dina Averina]], she qualified to all the apparatus finals taking gold in hoop, silver medals in ball, ribbon and placed 5th in clubs. Her next event at the [[2017 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2017 Baku World Cup]], Soldatova won silver in the all-around behind [[Arina Averina]], she qualified to all the apparatus finals taking gold in ball, silver medals in hoop, clubs and placed 5th in ribbon. On 19\u201321 May, at the [[2017 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships|2017 European Championships]] in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]], Soldatova was member of the Golden winning Russian Team (together with senior individuals [[Dina Averina]], [[Arina Averina]] and the junior group) scoring a total of 182.175 points which was more than 11 points ahead of their nearest competitor team [[Belarus]]. Soldatova qualified to 3 apparatus finals taking 2 silver medals in hoop, ball and finished 4th in ribbon behind [[Neviana Vladinova]].<ref name=Euros17/> Recovering from an ankle injury; Soldatova returned to competition on 4\u20136 August at the [[2017 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2017 Minsk World Challenge Cup]], she won gold in the all-around, she qualified in all 4 apparatus finals however mistake ridden routines and imprecise elements, after taking a silver in hoop behind [[Neviana Vladinova]], she finished 5th in ball, 6th in clubs, 4th in ribbon in her latter 3 apparatus. On 9 August, during the Russian team's control training selection process for the [[2017 Summer Universiade]], Soldatova was not selected to represent Russia in the rhythmic gymnastics universiade participants, the 2 representatives were [[Iuliia Bravikova]] and [[Ekaterina Selezneva]]. [[Irina Viner]] has also stated that Soldatova will not participate at the [[2017 World Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships|2017 World Championships]] as she has not fully recovered from her injury, she is still heavily recovering not just physically, but mentally.<ref name=Injury17/>\nOn 5\u20136 November, Soldatova competed at the [[Dalia Kutkait\u0117|2017 Dalia Kutkaite Cup]] winning the all-around gold with a total of 74.850 points, a 0.5 ahead of silver medalist [[Katsiaryna Halkina]].<ref>http://sc.bns.lt/view/item/246529</ref>\n\n====2018 Season====\nIn 2018, Soldatova started the season at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2018 Grand Prix Moscow]], where she placed 4th in all-around. She qualified to two apparatus finals, where she won silver with clubs and ribbon. At the [[Russian Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships|2018 Russian National Championships]], she won the silver medal behind the defending champion [[Dina Averina]].\n\nOn 30 March \u2013 1 April, Soldatova began with the world cup events competing at the [[2018 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2018 Sofia World Cup]] where she won the gold medal at the all-around. She qualified in all the apparatus finals, winning gold with hoop and ball, a bronze with clubs and finishing 4th with  ribbon. On 20\u201322 April, at the [[2018 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2018 Tashkent World Cup]], Soldatova won gold in the all-around posting a new personal best total of 77.050 points. She swept all the gold medals in the apparatus finals with high scores in hoop(19.900), ball(19.600), clubs(18.000) and ribbon(18.300). On 4\u20136 May, Soldatova competed at the [[2018 FIG Rhythmic Gymnastics World Cup Series|2018 Guadalajara World Challenge Cup]] where she won silver in the all-around (72.750) behind [[Linoy Ashram]]. She qualified in all apparatus finals however mistakes with hoop and ball led to 6th and 7th place respectively in those finals. She still won silver in clubs behind [[Arina Averina]] and won gold in the last event with ribbon (18.650).\n\nOn 16\u201317 May, Soldatova competed at the [[Rhythmic Gymnastics Grand Prix Series|2018 Holon Grand Prix]] and won silver in the all-around with a total of 75.750 points behind teammate [[Arina Averina]]. She qualified for the hoop and clubs finals. However she withdrew from the events schedule due to injury, and it was later revealed she sustained a fracture in her left leg. She was in an orthopedic cast and was off the carpet for 4 weeks, then resumed training in early July, joining the Russian national training camp in [[Croatia]].\n\n==== 2019 Season ====\nSoldatova won four gold medals at the Tashkent World Cup in April 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ssr_backend/|title=4 gold medals for Aleksandra Soldatova at Tashkent World Cup|website=UEG Gymnastics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> and five gold medals at the 2019 Guadalajara World Challenge Cup in early May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ssr_backend/|title=Aleksandra Soldatova sweeps the Guadalajara gold medals|website=UEG Gymnastics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> On 19 May 2019, she won two silver medals - in ball and ribbon - at the European Championships in Baku.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-sports.org/gymnastics-european-rhythmic-gymnastics-championships-results-2019-women-epf94396.html|title=Gymnastics : European Rhythmic Gymnastics Championships 2019 - Results Women|website=www.the-sports.org|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> In September at the Portim\u00e3o World Challenge Cup, Soldatova won the all-around, but fainted backstage during the apparatus finals and subsequently withdrew from the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/sport/468425-alexandra-soldatova-faints-rhythmic-gymnastics/|title=Russian world champion gymnast Alexandra Soldatova sparks concern after passing out at competition|website=RT International|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==== 2020 Season ====\nRussian media reported that on 5 February Soldatova was taken to the Sklifosovskiy Institute in Moscow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tass.ru/obschestvo/7700153|title=\u0412\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0433\u0438\u043c\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u044b \u0421\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439|website=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> due to injuries on her left arm from a suicide attempt.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/abci-historia-tras-presunto-suicidio-aleksandra-soldatova-202002071009_noticia.html|title=La historia tras el presunto suicidio de Aleksandra Sold\u00e1tova|date=2020-02-07|website=abc|language=es|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> At the hospital she was diagnosed with bulimia.<ref name=\":0\" /> Soldatova later stated through her coach's Instagram account that she had accidentally cut herself with a knife while making breakfast and gone to the hospital.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tass.ru/sport/7702181|title=\u0421\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0448\u043e\u043a\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043a\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0434\u0430|website=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> She said that she would take time off to treat her bulimia, which she has been suffering from for the past two years, and wants to begin training again once she is healthy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tass.ru/sport/7719543|title=\u0413\u0438\u043c\u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043a\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0443\u0437\u0443 \u0432 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\u0435 \u0438\u0437-\u0437\u0430 \u0431\u0443\u043b\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0438|website=\u0422\u0410\u0421\u0421|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympicchannel.com/en/stories/news/detail/aleksandra-soldatova-bulimia-gymnastics/|title=Aleksandra Soldatova: My life was divided between sport and struggling with this illness|website=Olympic Channel|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== Gymnastics technique ==\nSoldatova is known for her [[Flexibility (anatomy)|flexible body difficulties]] and [[pivot turn]]s, she has executed a [[Pivot turn|quintuple penchee turn]] and a [[Pivot turn|quadruple ring pivot]] in competitions. She can also complete a quadruple double backscale pivot.\n\n==Routine music information==\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=col|Year\n!scope=col|Apparatus\n!scope=col|Music title<ref>{{cite web|title= Soldatova RG music list |url=http://www.rgforum.no/music/searchresults.php?gymnast_lastname=soldatova&gymnast_firstname=&nation=&apparatus=&tidsrom_fra=&music_title=&music_from=&music_composer=&lagtinn_etter_dato=01&lagtinn_etter_mnd=01&lagtinn_etter_aar=2004&programtype_individuell=on&status_godkjent=on |publisher= RGforum.no }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row rowspan=1|